Association of California School Administrators posted a video to playlist ACSA Campus Tour.
August 4 at 10:00 AM ·

The ACSA Campus Tour stops in Perris to talk with Triple Crown principal Deni Seagrave. She attended school in the Val Verde Unified School District and she described the experience of leading a school in that district during COVID-19. She also explains the strategy she and her team have put together to replicate the STEM/STEAM experience in a distance learning environment.

How to wear your Face Covering Correctly:
Wash your hands before putting on your face covering.
Put it over your nose and mouth and secure it under your chin.
Try to fit it snugly against the sides of your face.
Make sure you can breathe easily.

* Avoid close contact with others

* Cover coughs and sneezes
* Pick up food at drive-throughs or at the curb. Do not dine-in.

post_text:
Everyone reacts differently to stressful situations like COVID-19. You may feel anxious, mad, sad, or overwhelmed. Find ways to reduce your stress to help yourself and the people you care about.

Learn the common signs of stress.
Make time to unwind and do activities you enjoy.
Talk with family and friends by phone, text, or email.
If you or a loved one is feeling overwhelmed, get support 24/7 by calling 1-800-985-5990 or text TalkWithUs to 66746.
Learn more about stress and coping during the COVID-19 outbreak: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/managing-stress-anxiety.html

Picking up takeout food while slowing the spread of COVID-19?

Order & pay online or over the phone when possible.
Accept take-out without in-person contact or stay at least 6 feet away from others.
Wash your hands with soap and water or use hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol after bringing home your food.
Learn more about taking essential trips at this time: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/daily-life-coping/essential-goods-services.html

Do you think you may have COVID-19? If you think you’re sick, follow guidance about when to call your doctor:

Monitor your symptoms
Call ahead before visiting your doctor
Avoid close contact with others when you’re out
Most people who get COVID-19 can take care of themselves at home. If you need to see a doctor, take precautions to protect yourself and others around you. See more: https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/if-you-are-sick/steps-when-sick.html

post_text:
Are you aware that older adults and people who have serious underlying medical conditions like chronic lung disease, serious heart conditions, and diabetes are at higher risk for severe illness from COVID-19? If your parent or another relative is an older adult or has a serious underlying medical condition, they should be aware of preparations to take:
* Stay home if possible
* Avoid close contact with people who are sick
* Take everyday preventive actions: wash hands often and avoid touching face, nose, and eyes
* Have over-the-counter medicines, medical supplies (like tissues), and extra necessary prescriptions
* Have extra household items and groceries on hand
* Make a plan for what to do if they get sick
* Routinely clean and disinfect surfaces and objects that are touched often
* Consult with their healthcare provider if they have symptoms of COVID-19
Learn more at cdc.gov/coronavirus

shared_text:
Riverside County Office of Education
June 20, 2019 at 4:33 PM ·

Even as spring turns to summer, we continue to recognize the outstanding educators honored at the Celebrating Educators event in May. Meet Dawnyelle DeLongchamp, District Psychologist, El Potrero Preschool, in the Val Verde Unified School District, and the Riverside County Site Support Employee of the Year. As the first contact with students’ families when they enter the district, Dawnyelle works to build trust with parents and ensure they are invested early in their child’s education. She provides psychological services to students onsite and believes it is important to reduce stigma around mental health issues. Dawnyelle is described by a peer as a “leader that is fair, a teacher that is generous, and a psychologist that is dedicated.” Congratulations, Dawnyelle!

Meet all of the Riverside County Educators of the Year:
https://www.rcoe.us/celebrating-educators/

post_text: Kudos to CDE for hosting this event. It was an honor for our superintendent Michael R Michael McCormick to be included on this expert panel.
shared_text:
California Department of Education
May 7, 2019 at 12:17 PM ·

Yesterday, State Superintendent Tony Thurmond and a group of distinguished researchers and practitioners gathered to discuss their data and experiences regarding a hot topic in education: quality measures of predicting college success and the equity implications for accurately assessing students’ knowledge and skills.

Thanks to all the panelists:

• Michal Kurlaender, Professor of Education Policy at UC Davis School of Education

• Young Whan Choi, Manager of Performance Assessments at Oakland Unified School District

• Claude Steele, Professor of Psychology at Stanford University's Department of Psychology

• James Popham, Emeritus Professor in the UCLA Graduate School of Education & Information Studies

• Michael McCormick, Superintendent at Val Verde Unified School District

shared_text:
Nobel Prize
January 14, 2019 at 11:37 PM ·

Today we remember the extraordinary Martin Luther King Jr, who was born #onthisday in 1929.

King was awarded the 1964 Nobel Peace Prize for his non-violent campaign against racism. He adhered to Gandhi's philosophy of nonviolence and began his struggle in 1955 to persuade the US Government to declare the policy of racial discrimination in the southern states unlawful.

Learn more: https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/peace/1964/king/facts/

shared_text:
Riverside County Office of Education
July 10, 2018 at 8:06 AM ·

Meet Vista Verde Middle School Attendance Technician and Riverside County Classified Employee of the Year, Lindsay Brancato. Lindsay always wanted to serve and help people, and found her calling working with students, parents, and educators at the Val Verde Unified School District.

Ms. Brancato’s efforts to launch a STEAM-focused attendance recovery program on Saturdays has garnered countywide attention and helped recover more than $5 million dollars in attendance funds in 2016-2017. As a result, Val Verde USD posted one of the highest attendance rates among all school districts in Riverside County.

Read more about Lindsay and her fellow Celebrating Educator honorees at https://www.rcoe.us/celebrating-educators.

post_text:
At Val Verde Unified School District we understand that technology is a part of our everyday lives. We believe in the power of staying engaged with the world from our connected devices. This year we became a 1 to 1 district, meaning we provided chromebooks to all of our students to take home in an effort to broaden and increase their exposure to 21st-century skills.

We also understand the importance that time away from these devices has on the safety and health of our students. This is why we are starting a “lights out” initiative with our chromebooks in the hands of our elementary aged students. Starting today, chromebooks assigned to our elementary students have had a filter installed that will prohibit them from using their district-issued devices between the hours of 10pm-6am.

The filter has been installed remotely and no other steps are required for this change to take place.
